Statement: I hereby agree that the facts I have submitted are my own, and that I grant a license for Pryaxis Limited, 
or designated entities by Pryaxis Limited, the ability to use this data in a way to promote future Pryaxis services.

1.Hurricanes are large, spiraling tropical storms that can pack wind speeds of over 160 mph and 
unleash more than 2.4 trillion gallons of rain a day.
2.The deadliest U.S. hurricane on record was a Category 4 storm that hit the island city of Galveston, Texas, on Sept. 8, 1900. 
Some 8,000 people lost their lives when the island was destroyed by 15-ft waves and 130-mph winds.
3.In the Atlantic, hurricane season starts June 1, while in the Pacific it starts May 15. Both end on November 30.
4.When they come onto land, the heavy rain, strong winds and heavy waves can damage buildings, 
trees and cars. The heavy waves are called a storm surge.
5.40% of the hurricanes that occur in the United States hit Florida.
